"Pashova L., Yovev I.","Geodetic studies of the influence of climate change on the Black sea level trend",2010,"Journal of Environmental Protection and Ecology","11","2",,"791","801",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77954977366&partnerID=40&md5=b084e4c69048c95e89f613445049eaee","Central Laboratory of Geodesy, Bulgarian Academy of Sciences, Acad. G. Bonchev Street, 1113 Sofia, Bulgaria","Pashova, L., Central Laboratory of Geodesy, Bulgarian Academy of Sciences, Acad. G. Bonchev Street, 1113 Sofia, Bulgaria; Yovev, I., Central Laboratory of Geodesy, Bulgarian Academy of Sciences, Acad. G. Bonchev Street, 1113 Sofia, Bulgaria","In this paper the problem for establishing the Black sea level trend related to the global climate change is discussed. It is well known that the mean sea level is a close approximation of the geopotential surface geoid (vertical datum), which is the true zero surface for measuring physical elevations. Definition characteristics of geoid surface are considered in two aspects (geometrical and gravimetric model) in accordance with the high accuracy and temporal-spatial resolution of modern geodetic measuring techniques. The possibility of 'absolute' sea level change determination using Global Navigation Satellite System (GNSS) stations collocated to the tide gauges, precise levelling and gravimetric measurements of geodetic points to connect independent geodetic systems to a one world reference system are considered. The geodetic measurements in the Black sea region will contribute to the complex studies of the World Ocean and open seas, and to find out the correlations between trend estimates obtained from different type of data. Long-term sea level changes are statistically significant and it is a matter of future more precise determination of their values. For that purpose it is needed a comprehensive, interdisciplinary research in terms of incorporating ancillary data types and various geophysical models as well.","Climate change; GPS; Gravimetry; Levelling; Mean sea level","climate change; geodesy; geoid; geopotential; GNSS; GPS; gravimetry; interdisciplinary approach; leveling; sea level change; Black Sea",,,,,,"(2007) IPCC WGI Fourth Assessment Report, Climate Change 2007: The Physical Science Basis, Summary for Policymakers, , http:www.aaas.org/news/press_room/climate_change/media/4th_spm2feb07.pdf, IPCC available at; Church, J.A., White, N.J., A 20th century acceleration in global sea-level rise (2006) Geophysical Research Letters, 33, pp. L01602. , doi:10.1029/2005GL024826; Wöppelmann, G., Martin Miguez, B., Bouin, M.-N., Altamimi, Z., Geocentric sea-level trend estimates from GPS analyses at relevant tide gauges world-wide (2007) Global and Planetary Change, 57, p. 396; Pashova, L., Yovev, I., Geoid modeling for the black sea and future prospects (2007) Maritime Industry, Ocean Engineering and Coastal Resources, pp. 761-768. , (Eds G. Soares, Kolev). Taylor & Francis Group, London, ISBN 978-0-415-45523-7; Burša, M., Groten, E., Kenyon, S., Kouba, J., Rad'Ej, K., Vatrt, V., Vojtiskova, M., Earth's dimension specified by geoidal geopotential (2002) Stud. Geophys. Geod., 46, p. 1; (2003) IERS Conventions, p. 127. , D. D. MCCARTHY, G. PETIT (Eds) IERS Conventions Centre, IERS Technical Note No 32, Vlg. des Bundesamts für Kartographie und Geodäsie, Frankfurt a. M; Bursa, M., Kenyon, St., Kouba, J., Sima, Z., Vatrt, V., Vitek, V., Vojtiskova, M., The geopotential value Wo for specifying the relativistic atomic time scale and a global vertical reference system (2007) J. Geodesy, 81, p. 103. , doi:10.1007/s00190-006-0091-3; Douglas, B.C., Global sea level rise: A redetermination (1997) Surv. Geophys. Res., 18, p. 279; Kuo, Ch.-Y., Determination and characterization of 20th century global sea level rise (2006) Report no 478, p. 168. , The Ohio State University, Columbus; Peltier, W.R., Global sea level rise and glacial isostatic adjustment (1999) Global and Planetary Change, 20, p. 93